# Web Theme And Tailwind

## Avoid AI-Slop Styling

- Do not add decorative rails, left borders, accent strips, blobs, glow stacks, glassmorphism, generic gradients, floating SaaS cards, or oversized blurred shadows as default visual interest.
- Decoration should earn its place by reinforcing the archival atlas concept, clarifying hierarchy, or communicating state. If it is only there to make an empty space feel designed, remove it.
- Prefer typography, spacing, page composition, subtle dividers, paper-toned surfaces, and restrained texture over ornamental flourishes.

## Visual Direction

- The visual direction is an archival atlas page: warm paper backgrounds, ink-like foreground text, muted botanical and map tones, and a sharper accent for active graph selections or primary actions.
- The palette should feel researched, local-first, and exploratory rather than SaaS-generic. Favor parchment, moss, mineral blue, ochre, and dark ink relationships over bright default Tailwind hues.
- In light mode, preserve the paper-and-ink feeling with warm surfaces and soft borders. In dark mode, keep the same archive mood with deep umber backgrounds, readable warm text, and accents that feel illuminated rather than neon.
- Use stronger color only to communicate state, selection, graph meaning, or action. Most surfaces should stay quiet so graph structure and word relationships carry the visual weight.
- Prefer atlas-page composition over stacked app cards: paint hero copy, graph headings, and primary page structure directly onto the background with generous spacing. Use `Divider.vue` for standalone section dividers instead of putting separator borders directly on sections.
- Use `PageMain.vue` for top-level route content in `apps/web/src/views/` so desktop page width, horizontal padding, vertical rhythm, and page text color stay consistent. Do not put `mx-auto`, `max-w-*`, or page padding directly on view-level `<main>` elements unless a route deliberately needs a different layout shell.
- Use bordered surfaces only where containment helps interaction or scanning, such as search forms, popovers, node details, and small index/reference groups.
- Keep corners sharp and paper-like. Prefer `rounded-md` for contained page surfaces and about `6px` in component CSS. Reserve full pills for badges and compact controls only.
- Graph canvas backgrounds should read as map texture rather than decorative blobs. Use faint graticules, route/contour marks, grain, and vignettes; any map pattern inside the graph should pan and zoom with the graph viewport.
- Prefer borders, paper-toned surfaces, typography, spacing, and restrained texture for hierarchy. Small shadows are acceptable when they imitate paper separation, popovers, or selected graph marks; keep them close, low-contrast, and named through theme tokens such as `shadow-paper`, `shadow-panel`, or `shadow-overlay`.
- Do not scatter arbitrary `shadow-[...]` or heavy `drop-shadow(...)` values through components. Add a semantic shadow token in `apps/web/src/styles.css` when a new depth level is genuinely needed.
- Use Tailwind utilities for component layout, spacing, typography, borders, and interaction states in `apps/web`.
- Use semantic color utilities from `apps/web/src/styles.css` instead of raw palette classes. Prefer `bg-background`, `bg-surface`, `bg-surface-muted`, `bg-surface-raised`, `text-text`, `text-text-page-muted`, `text-text-muted`, `border-border`, `border-border-strong`, `bg-accent`, `text-accent`, `bg-accent-soft`, and `text-danger`.
- Use `text-text-page-muted` for secondary text painted directly on the atlas page/background. Keep `text-text-muted` for secondary text on contained surfaces such as `bg-surface`, `bg-surface-muted`, `bg-surface-raised`, popovers, cards, controls, and graph panels.
- Add new theme colors as CSS variables in `apps/web/src/styles.css`, expose them through `@theme inline`, then use the semantic utility in components. Do not scatter one-off values such as `bg-slate-900`, `text-emerald-600`, or arbitrary hex colors through Vue templates.
- Treat dark mode as first class. Any new surface, text, border, graph, or state color should work through the existing light/dark token values rather than through isolated `dark:` overrides.
- Use `dark:` variants for structural differences only when tokens cannot express the behavior cleanly.
- Keep graph-specific colors semantic. Prefer tokens such as `graph-node`, `graph-root`, `graph-edge`, `ancestor`, `descendant`, and `borrowed` for graph visualizations.
- The app has an explicit light/dark toggle that sets `light` or `dark` on the document root and uses system preference as the initial fallback. Preserve that behavior when touching theme code.

## Page Backgrounds

- The global page background should read as old parchment or tea-stained paper, not as a modern decorative gradient field.
- Prefer layered CSS backgrounds using theme tokens: a warm base color, low-opacity inline SVG turbulence grain, soft irregular radial tea stains, a subtle vignette, and a very quiet atlas grid when useful.
- Do not use obvious diagonal stripe fields, hard-edged bands, blobs, glow stacks, or decorative wash layers that overpower the page content.
- Tile only layers that are actually seamless, such as SVG noise/grain or a faint grid. Large stains, vignettes, and broad wash gradients should usually be `no-repeat`; repeating them creates visible horizontal and vertical tile boundaries.
- If an inline SVG data URL is used for grain, keep it small, local to `apps/web/src/styles.css`, low contrast, and color it like brown ink or paper fiber. Do not add a separate asset file unless there is a clear need for an authored texture.
- Keep the background texture strong enough to make the page feel tactile, but quiet enough that body text, graph labels, form fields, and result lists remain easy to read.

## Surfaces

- Use surfaces where containment helps interaction or scanning: search forms, result controls, popovers, node details, current examples, error notices, loading frames, and small index/reference groups.
- Do not wrap every page section in a card. Page headings, explanatory copy, and primary section structure should often be painted directly on the parchment with dividers and spacing.
- Dense indexes and long result lists should read like atlas lists, not card stacks. Prefer `border-y` plus `divide-y` rows and subtle hover fills over per-row borders, shadows, or raised slips.
- Treat contained surfaces as archival slips laid on parchment, not glossy app cards. Use translucent warm paper fills such as `bg-surface/55`, `bg-surface/60`, or `bg-surface/65` so the page texture can breathe through.
- Use lighter fills for nested clickable slips, around `bg-surface/45`, with hover states that rise only slightly, such as `hover:bg-surface/75` or `hover:bg-surface-muted`.
- Do not put a local paper texture on every surface. The global parchment background already provides texture; add per-component paper grain only when the element should feel like a separate tactile object, such as a solid CTA, selected control, popover, feature card, or compact reference slip.
- For nested navigational/reference slips, prefer a restrained treatment: light `bg-surface/35` to `bg-surface/45`, hairline `border-border`, optional `shadow-paper`, subtle paper grain when it clarifies the object, and hover states around `hover:bg-surface/70` or `hover:bg-surface/75`.
- Keep borders hairline and ink-like with `border-border` or `border-border-strong`. Prefer borders and paper tone over stronger shadows.
- Keep shadows close and low contrast. `shadow-paper` is enough for most static page surfaces; reserve heavier overlay shadows for floating UI.
- Keep corners sharp and paper-like. Prefer `rounded-[3px]` for view-level paper slips and `rounded-md` for controls, CTAs, popovers, and reusable component defaults. Reserve full pills for badges and compact metadata only.
- Primary action buttons may remain solid accent surfaces and can carry a quiet paper-fiber texture, but should still use restrained paper geometry, usually `rounded-md` rather than `rounded-lg`. Keep ghost/transparent controls visually flat unless an active state needs connection to an open surface.

## Typography

- Treat typography as a small system, not a place for per-component invention. Use the existing `font-sans` serif stack for prose, headings, entry content, graph labels, and most page text.
- Use `font-label` only for interface chrome: buttons, form labels, navigation, tabs, badges, menu items, compact metadata labels, and uppercase section eyebrows.
- Keep primary page headings large, heavy, and tightly tracked. Use `font-black` with negative tracking for hero/page titles only; do not apply this display treatment to cards, buttons, body text, or dense metadata.
- Use uppercase, letter-spaced label text sparingly and consistently: `font-label`, `font-bold` or `font-black`, `uppercase`, and `tracking-[0.12em]` to `tracking-[0.16em]`. Do not invent nearby tracking values unless the surrounding component already establishes them.
- Body copy, explanations, empty states, and source text should stay readable and quiet: normal serif text, restrained size changes, and `text-text-muted` only for secondary information.
- Interactive text should use the shared label style rather than bespoke weights or decorative fonts. Prefer existing `Button`, `IconButton`, `TextField`, `Combobox`, `MenuItem`, and navigation patterns before adding new typography classes.
- Do not add one-off font families, arbitrary `font-[...]`, arbitrary line-height, decorative italics, mixed-case label experiments, or raw CSS `font-family` declarations in Vue components. Add a semantic font token in `apps/web/src/styles.css` only if a distinct recurring text role genuinely needs it.

## Copy Content And Voice

- Review what the copy says before polishing how it sounds. The text should describe the user's task, result, or next step, not the implementation that produced it.
- Write UI copy in a clear, authoritative, straightforward, and unambiguous voice.
- Prefer short declarative sentences, concrete nouns, and active verbs. Tell the user what happened, what it means, and what to do next.
- Avoid hedging, filler, hype, cute phrasing, and vague labels. Do not say "maybe", "just", "magic", "supercharge", or "unlock" unless the product literally needs that meaning.
- Do not use em dashes in UI copy or documentation. Prefer a period, comma, colon, or a simpler sentence split.
- Use proper Unicode symbols in user-facing copy. Prefer `→` over ASCII `->` for relationships, transformations, paths, and sound-change notation.
- Keep implementation details out of user-facing copy. Do not mention imports, imported data, seed data, APIs, databases, edge types, metadata, backend/frontend code, or the data model unless the user is in an explicitly technical/admin context.
- Describe the user-visible result instead: a word page, source trail, lineage, entry, relationship, graph, search, path, match, index, or atlas.
- Frame the product as an archival language atlas. Prefer labels such as `Map the history of language`, `Word lineages`, `Doublets`, and `Sound changes` over narrow tool labels such as `lookup`.
- In public empty states, describe coverage without exposing local development mechanics. Prefer `No paths in the index yet` or `This example is not in the index yet` over `No imported matches`, `not in the local dataset`, or `import a broader seed set`.
- Use `step`, `link`, `relationship`, or `path` for user-facing traversal counts. Reserve `edge` and `node` for code, developer docs, and explicitly technical graph diagnostics.
- Do not make headings and labels repeat the same noun. If an eyebrow says `Graph examples`, the heading should add meaning, such as `Compare related words`, not repeat `Examples`.
- Preserve the archival atlas mood through precise language, not ornament. Favor words like `source`, `lineage`, `entry`, `relationship`, `search`, and `graph` when they match the feature.
- Button labels and errors should be direct: `Search`, `Reset`, `Close`, `No matches found`, `Import failed`, `Try another term`.

Example:

```vue
<PageMain>
  <section class="pb-8">
    <p class="font-label text-sm font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.12em] text-text-page-muted">Atlas section</p>
    <h1 class="text-5xl font-black tracking-[-0.06em]">Paint primary content on the page.</h1>
  </section>
  <Divider />
  <section class="rounded-[3px] border border-border bg-surface/60 p-5 shadow-paper">
    <p class="text-text-muted">Use contained surfaces for forms and reference slips.</p>
  </section>
  <section class="rounded-[3px] border border-border bg-surface/55 p-5 shadow-paper">
    <RouterLink class="grid gap-2 rounded-[3px] border border-border bg-surface/45 p-4 hover:bg-surface/75">
      Use lighter nested slips for choices.
    </RouterLink>
  </section>
</PageMain>
```
